<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-116-088  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 116 088.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Feb 5 1990 v7 n5 p15(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font standard tops users' wish lists at Forum. (BIS CAPInternational Inc. PC/Desktop Printing Conference)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Clarification of font standards is the chief concern expressed bydesktop-publishing users at the PC/Desktop Printing Conference inJan 1990.andP;  Users say that the ongoing confusion over PostScript,Apple/Microsoft, and HP font formats results in difficultyensuring that fonts on networked computers and printers arecompatible.andP;  Many users also wish for laser printers that outputonto 11 x 17-inch paper.andP;  Only QMS Inc currently offers such amachine.andP;  Other concerns include the need for inexpensive colorprinters, duplex monochrome printers, and combinationprinter/facsimile machines.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   BIS CAP International Inc. (conferences and meetings).andO;Topic:     Desktop publishingFontsConferencesUser NeedsStandardization.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;With 12,000 users, 11,000 workstations and 6,000 printing devices to manage,Linda Schreck would rather not have to worry about something so small as afont.andM;But she does.andM;&quot;Such a small part of the printing process creates more headaches on ournetworks,&quot; she said at a recent conference.andM;Schreck, who manages networks linking more than 30 buildings at LawrenceLivermore National Laboratory in Livermore, Calif., voiced several concernsechoed by many large-systems users during a roundtable session at lastmonth's BIS CAP International Inc.andP;  PC/Desktop Printing Conference inMonterey, Calif.andM;Among the solutions to her problems, Schreck said, would be a resolution ofthe ongoing confusion surrounding font standards, as well as the emergence oflaser printers that output onto 11-by-17-inch paper, inexpensive colorprinters and duplex monochrome models, and printers that also act as faxmachines.andM;One simple request topped a user wish list at the roundtable -- theestablishment of a standard font format that would ensure that fonts arecompatible among networked operating systems and printers.andM;A request to clear up the confusion over desktop-publishing font standardscame in a close second.andP;  With desktop publishing gaining prominence inwork-group sites, many users said they wish Microsoft Corp., IBM and AppleComputer Inc. would finally clear the air over when and how outline fontswill appear in various platforms.andM;With graphics printing on the rise at Livermore Labs, requests for11-by-17-inch printer capabilities have proliferated, especially frompublication and engineering departments, Shreck said.andP;  &quot;We have engineersprinting fancy maps and graphics who need the speed of a laser, but they'relimited by the small paper size [available in most laser printers],&quot; shesaid.andP;  Currently, only QMS Inc. offers a laser printer with the large-sizeprinting capabilities.andM;In addition to more large-size printers, Schreck would welcome lower pricesfor color printers.andP;  Although the prices of color PostScript printers havedropped dramatically in the past year, Schreck would like to see them be evenmore reasonable than the current low of $10,000.andM;For workaday business printing, an increase in less expensive, fasterprinters that print on two sides of the page would be a welcome sight atLivermore.andP;  Duplex printers let many departments, from editorial toengineering, be more creative and efficient with printing, Schreck said.andM;Schreck also said she sees a growing need for the much talked-about printersthat also function as fax machines.andM;User requests at the conference leaned more toward publishing issues thanconcerns of general business users, said Rob Auster, director of CAP'selectronic printing division and the event's moderator.andM;Although the conference focused on future printer strategies at firms such asIBM, Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard Co., Auster said next year's conferencewill be even more user-oriented.andP;  &quot;It's a good way for users to compare notesand let vendors know what they need,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>